          <td valign="top" width="1" ><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="18" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td  valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <BR><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="49124b996d565b5dd25de987151be49b" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr height="10"><td width="98%" bgcolor="#333333" height="10"><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="6" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td><td valign="bottom" align="right"><img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/tk.gif" width="103" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td valign="top" align="right">
<img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/bk.gif" width="92" height="24" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Onslaught Part 2<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.75)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=4008'>Lyle "Pikachu87" Waldman</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=4008&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 22, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Hi everybody! (OK, now you should say Hi, Dr. Nick!) Due to a few reviews I got on my last Onslaught article, I will write an article about what&#39;s new, not what&#39;s old.  Onslaught is not a particularly interesting set.  Most of the mechanics have been done before, so I&#39;m just goiing to go over those briefly for the benefit of new players.  I will concentrate on the meat of the new set.<br />
<br />
First, I will go over the old mechanics just to get it over with.  Cycling has returned.  Cycling was a mechanic from the Urza cycle which let you discard a card with cycling from your hand to draw a card by paying its cycling cost.  In the Urza cycle, this cost was 2 colorless mana.  In Onslaught, they use different costs.  There&#39;s a 5/6 creature for GG3 I think with cycling G2.  In Onslaught as well, some cycling cards have abilities that trigger when they&#39;re cycled.  For instance, this 5/6 fattie lets you do a Rampant Growth when you cycle it.<br />
<br />
Next, there&#39;s Fear.  All veteran Magic players remember the Black enchantment Fear.  It&#39;s BB to cast and enchanted creature cannot be blocked except by black or artifact creatures.  Many creatures have since had this ability built in.  The only thing that changes is that the wording on the card is now &quot;Fear&quot; and the other stuff is reminder text.<br />
<br />
The next thing that comes in Onslaught are the Chain spells.  These were done back in Alliances or Homelands with Chain Lightning and Chain Stasis.  These cards let you do something and then the target&#39;s controller or the target (if it&#39;s a player) may pay some mana to do the same thing to another target.  Chain Lightning was a Bolt for RRR which could chain other people for RRR.<br />
<br />
Kamahl returns in Onslaught.  This time, in my opinion, he&#39;s a lot better.  Kamhl Pit Fighter was a 6/1  for 5 who could tap for a Bolt, if I&#39;m not mistaken.  Kamahl Fist of Krosa is a 4/3 Druid Legend for GG4 who can turn a land into a 1/1 for G and Overrun at the speed of an instant for GGG2.<br />
<br />
Now onto the meat.  The good stuff.  The new stuff.  The interesting stuff.  In Onslaught, there&#39;s a new mechanic called &quot;Morph&quot;.  Morph is the ultimate bluff. Morph lets you play a creature face-down for 3 colorless as a 2/2 with no color, no abilities, no text, no type, no name, and no casting cost.  It&#39;s like a 2/2 generic token.  You can pay a card&#39;s Morph cost any time to turn it face-up at the speed of a Mana Source.  Mana Sources were (back in the days of 5th edition) the fastest spells there were.  They were even faster than interrupts so they couldn&#39;t be countered.  Any ability or effect which produced mana was a Mana Source.  If you look at an Urza&#39;s Saga Dark Ritual you&#39;ll see it called a Mana Source.  Morph abilities cannot be countered as they don&#39;t use the stack and they&#39;re not activated abilities either because they don&#39;t have a colon.  The problem with Morph is that you can play a card without Morph face-down as if it had Morph and no-one would know.  Your play group has to decide what to do in these circumstances.  If it was me, I&#39;d say that as soon as that card was flipped face-up, the owner of the card would have to forfeit immediately, even if they won the game.<br />
<br />
The fat of the set is called the Pit Fighter Legends.  In my Battle of Wits deck I used 4 of these 5 legends.  There&#39;s one for each color:<br />
<br />
Visara the Dreadful: BBB3 to cast 5/5 flyer tap to bury any creature.<br />
Jareth, Leotite Titan: WWW3 to cast 4/7 auto-Righteousness (when it blocks it gets +7+7) and W to gain protection from any color until end of turn.<br />
Silvos, Rogue Elemental: GGG3 to cast 8/5 trample G to regenerate.<br />
Arcanis the Omnipotent: UUU3 to cast 3/4 tap for Ancestral Recall (Draw 3 cards) bounces itself for UU2.<br />
Rorix Bladewing: RRR3 to cast 6/5 flying haste.<br />
<br />
As you can easily see, these 5 were based on the Avatars from Prophecy.  Avatar of Woe was a 6/6 fear who could tap to destroy any creature.  The difference between Destroy and Bury is that Buried creatures can&#39;t be regenerated.  Avatar of Hope was a 4/9 flyer.  Avatar of Might was an 8/8 trampler.  Avatar of Fury was a 6/5 Flying Firebreathing.  The only one that was different was Avatar of Will.  Avatar of Will was a Mahamoti Djinn which had the reduced cost ability of all the Avatars and is nothing like Arcanis.  In my opinion, the ranking of these legends is completely different from my ranking of the Avatars;<br />
<br />
Pit Fighers (best to worst):<br />
Jareth, Leotite Titan<br />
Arcanis the Omnipotent<br />
Silvos, Rogue Elemental<br />
Visara the Dreadful<br />
Rorix Bladewing<br />
<br />
Avatars (best to worst):<br />
Woe<br />
Might<br />
Fury<br />
Will<br />
Hope<br />
<br />
Keep in mind this is just my opinion.  The reason I chose this order of the legends is this: Jareth can protect himself from anything.  Give him that enchantment that lets him block any number of creatures and for WWWWW he becomes the ultimate creature destroyer.  He can take infinite punishment because he&#39;s protection from everything and he dishes out 11 points of punishment every time he blocks.  Just throw in a Fling and you&#39;re on your way to victory.  The reason I voted Arcanis as second best is because of his Recall ability.  In a Blue Counter/stall drawing cards is your best resource.  The more cards you can draw the better.  He can also save himself from doom by bouncing himself.  I said Silvos was third not because of his power, but because of Green&#39;s power.  Sure, Visara can kill him on command, but consider this:<br />
<br />
1st turn: Forest, Llanowar Elf.<br />
Second turn: Forest, triple Wild Growth or a few more elves<br />
Third turn: Silvos, Rogue Elemental<br />
<br />
You can attack your opponent for 24 damage by the time your opponent can even hope of getting Visara out.  Or better yet, fourth turn kill:<br />
<br />
(See above for first 2 turns)<br />
Turn 3: Silvos, forest, and Wild Growth<br />
Turn 4: Attack with Silvos, quadruple Giant Growth and quadruple Wax (that&#39;s a 28/23 trampler or turn 4 buddy...it don&#39;t get much better than that)<br />
<br />
Ok, I know you&#39;ll never get those cards in your hand, but 4 Wild Mights if your opponent is tapped out will do the same job.<br />
<br />
The reason I chose Visara for fourth is because Rorix is just so utterly horrible that he doesn&#39;t deserve the 4th position.  I mean he&#39;s a 5/6 flying haste for 6!  And he&#39;s not even green!  If he was green I&#39;d consider giving him the fourth spot but he&#39;s red!  How many people can kill red by the time they can get it out?  Green trample can, just with my all-common Silvos example (well...Silvos is rare but the rest are common), Blue can chump block with mini flyers, Black can have Visara out by turn 2 if they&#39;re really lucky (Turn 1 Swamp turn 2 Swamp double ritual and Visara), White can gain enough life that Haste won&#39;t help and a flying Jareth (with the help of Wonder, Levitation, Flight, Jump, or Leap) can stop Rorix in his tracks.<br />
<br />
Enough about the Pit Fighters.  The next important thing in Onslaught are the Creature Type spells and legends.  I don&#39;t really know what these are about, as I&#39;ve only seen a picture of one of them, but they basically give you a really cool effect if you have a lot of a certain creature type in your deck.  Gravespine Soverign, a zombie Lord, lets you tap 5 zombies to put a creature from any graveyard into play under your control.<br />
<br />
That&#39;s all I know about Onslaught right now.  Until next time, Chao! <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magic/articles/articles.php?id=4104&view=1&PHPSESSID=49124b996d565b5dd25de987151be49b'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magic/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=49124b996d565b5dd25de987151be49b'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magic/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=49124b996d565b5dd25de987151be49b'> become a registered member</a></font><BR></td></tr></table>
